<p></p>.<p>Inflammation of the bony area (tailbone or <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/low_back_pain_pictures_slideshow/article.htm" rel="slide" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">coccyx</a>) located between the buttocks is referred to as <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/coccydynia/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">coccydynia</a>. Coccydynia is associated with <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_management/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pain</a> and tenderness at the tip of the tailbone between the buttocks. The <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pain_quiz/quiz.htm" rel="quiz" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pain</a> is often worsened by sitting.</p>.<p>
Coccydynia is often caused by an injury, but may occur  seemingly spontaneously. There are many causes of <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/coccydynia/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">tailbone pain</a> which can mimic coccydynia, including <a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/sciatica/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">sciatica</a>, infection, 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/pilonidal_cyst/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">pilonidal cysts</a>, and 
<a href="https://www.medicinenet.com/broken_bone_types_of_bone_fractures/article.htm" rel="dt" onclick="wmdTrack('embd-lnk');">fractured bone</a>.</p>.<p class="credits">REFERENCE:<br><br>Kasper, D.L., et al., eds. <i>Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 19th Ed</i>. United States: McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.</p>